of. George fan. All right. Time to talk about my rule which is

571
00:28:05,592 --> 00:28:09,433
make your enemies actually different. First let's zoom into

572
00:28:09,473 --> 00:28:11,534
this word actually. What do I mean by that?

573
00:28:15,162 --> 00:28:20,288
In this case, I mean making it so each new enemy is tackled in a different way. Think of some of

574
00:28:20,308 --> 00:28:25,294
the games you played where the enemy design was exceptional. I bet in each case there was a high

575
00:28:25,334 --> 00:28:30,279
density of enemies that you had to use different methods to defeat. The reason I have Super Mario

576
00:28:30,319 --> 00:28:33,803
in this slide here is because it does such a great job of meeting this criteria.

577
00:28:34,564 --> 00:28:37,105
Take note of the feeling you have right now when looking at

578
00:28:37,125 --> 00:28:39,225
this set of bad guys. Remembering all the different

579
00:28:39,265 --> 00:28:42,546
ways you used to defeat them. If you are ever unsure about

580
00:28:42,606 --> 00:28:45,846
enemy design, I recommend analyzing the first Super Mario

581
00:28:46,627 --> 00:28:49,087
and see how it did things as a clean example of enemy design

582
00:28:49,107 --> 00:28:53,348
done right. Sometimes we set out to make a game with a lot of

583
00:28:53,428 --> 00:28:57,209
enemy variety. On the surface they look different enough. And

584
00:28:57,249 --> 00:28:58,269
they seem to do different things.

585
00:28:59,527 --> 00:29:02,529
but to the player fighting enemies becomes monotonous and

586
00:29:02,569 --> 00:29:04,991
each new encounter doesn't bring enough uniqueness to the table.

587
00:29:06,071 --> 00:29:08,733
And we're left with a game that feels like you just fought a

588
00:29:08,753 --> 00:29:11,676
bunch of the same thing. Today I want to teach you how to avoid

589
00:29:11,696 --> 00:29:15,418
that. To help us along I'm going to introduce a tool called

590
00:29:15,538 --> 00:29:19,221
player brain-o-vision. It's a way for us to remember to get

591
00:29:19,321 --> 00:29:22,323
into the player's brain as this is the most important

592
00:29:22,363 --> 00:29:28,468
perspective. So let's meet our player. Naturally our player has

593
00:29:28,528 --> 00:29:28,828
a brain.

594
00:29:30,253 --> 00:29:33,394
Let's try using player brain o vision and imagine what this

595
00:29:33,414 --> 00:29:38,055
guy is thinking. Let's try to see what his brain sees. Based

596
00:29:38,095 --> 00:29:41,016
on this guy's expression, I'm going to say he's playing Bill

597
00:29:42,037 --> 00:29:46,818
and Ted's excellent video game adventure. All right. So let's

598
00:29:46,838 --> 00:29:50,039
get into this. I'm going to start with some don't dos. Here

599
00:29:50,059 --> 00:29:52,480
are things you don't want to do when your goal is to make

600
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:54,101
enemies actually different.

601
00:29:55,470 --> 00:29:57,751
First pitfall happens when we have two enemies that are

602
00:29:57,791 --> 00:30:01,233
identical and think, oh, we'll just change the look of one of

603
00:30:01,253 --> 00:30:05,475
them. That will be enough. Do this over and over again and

604
00:30:05,495 --> 00:30:08,856
you'll have the most boring game of all time. The problem here is

605
00:30:08,936 --> 00:30:11,477
that the two enemies are doing the same thing. The player

606
00:30:11,497 --> 00:30:15,079
doesn't handle the skeleton any differently than the mummy. So

607
00:30:15,099 --> 00:30:17,720
they'll store both of these in their brain occupying the same

608
00:30:17,760 --> 00:30:21,382
space and our brains tend to clump things together in order

609
00:30:21,402 --> 00:30:23,683
to keep up with all the information we need to process.

610
00:30:25,252 --> 00:30:28,234
Now the player's goal is to beat the game. To that extent, the

611
00:30:28,274 --> 00:30:30,836
player doesn't care that the mummy looks different from the

612
00:30:30,856 --> 00:30:34,539
skeleton. In its efficiency, the brain will squeeze these two

613
00:30:34,579 --> 00:30:38,262
together into just one enemy. And that's what we want to

614
00:30:38,302 --> 00:30:42,245
avoid as we're not adding any true enemy variety here.

615
00:30:43,767 --> 00:30:47,110
Even lazier than changing just the look is changing one color

616
00:30:47,410 --> 00:30:50,793
to another. I certainly didn't think of this gray fish from

617
00:30:50,853 --> 00:30:54,415
super Mario as a brand new enemy type. I'll cut them some slack

618
00:30:54,435 --> 00:30:57,117
because they were up against some extreme memory limitations

619
00:30:57,377 --> 00:31:00,840
at the time. But nowadays color shifts, they just don't pass for

620
00:31:00,880 --> 00:31:04,683
brand new enemies anymore. An abundance of them can often make

621
00:31:04,703 --> 00:31:07,405
your game feel cheap and most of the time you're better off with

622
00:31:07,445 --> 00:31:10,267
just one solid enemy instead of two pallet swapped enemies.

623
00:31:11,796 --> 00:31:15,318
One more thing is to not think of small changes in HP, damage

624
00:31:15,358 --> 00:31:19,501
and speed as brand new enemies. A little bit is okay, but if

625
00:31:19,721 --> 00:31:22,503
every bad guy in your game can be defined as just some degree

626
00:31:22,523 --> 00:31:25,605
of these three variables, you're doing something wrong. The

627
00:31:25,645 --> 00:31:29,267
difference between 500 and 510 is small enough that once again,

628
00:31:29,588 --> 00:31:32,530
the player's brain will meld these two together into just one

629
00:31:32,590 --> 00:31:37,052
bad guy with about 500 HP. All right. Now that we've covered

630
00:31:37,093 --> 00:31:37,813
some don't dos,

631
00:31:38,779 --> 00:31:42,122
It's time to take a look at some doodoos. I've got a big doodoo

632
00:31:42,162 --> 00:31:45,605
for you to take a look at. And I'm going to call it attributes

633
00:31:45,765 --> 00:31:49,648
of differentiation. Basically these are qualities enemies

634
00:31:49,688 --> 00:31:52,090
might have that would make them play differently from one

635
00:31:52,130 --> 00:31:55,813
another. You might think of them as sort of avenues to explore

636
00:31:56,473 --> 00:31:59,396
while you're trying to make your enemies actually different. In

637
00:31:59,436 --> 00:32:02,098
this section of the talk I'll provide you with some examples

638
00:32:02,138 --> 00:32:05,841
of attributes I find myself using again and again. The first

639
00:32:05,881 --> 00:32:06,702
one of these is movement.

640
00:32:07,534 --> 00:32:10,097
We can often make the player handle the enemy differently by

641
00:32:10,157 --> 00:32:13,560
simply introducing new movement patterns. In Super Mario, these

642
00:32:13,640 --> 00:32:16,062
enemies all have distinct styles of movement and the player needs

643
00:32:16,102 --> 00:32:19,145
to account for each one differently. But be careful you

644
00:32:19,165 --> 00:32:21,828
don't spend time making things have special movement when in

645
00:32:21,868 --> 00:32:24,490
the end it gets handled by the player just the same as

646
00:32:24,510 --> 00:32:27,834
something else. In this hypothetical game, we've designed

647
00:32:27,894 --> 00:32:32,058
two enemies, a bird that moves in a zigzag and a bat that moves

648
00:32:32,098 --> 00:32:32,698
in a sine wave.

649
00:32:34,578 --> 00:32:37,420
There might be cases where this difference is significant, but

650
00:32:37,480 --> 00:32:40,021
for the most part I see players handling these two movement

651
00:32:40,041 --> 00:32:43,723
patterns in the exact same way. Again, not good if our goal is

652
00:32:43,763 --> 00:32:46,804
to make enemies actually different. Stuff like this can

653
00:32:46,844 --> 00:32:49,985
be found out through play testing, but using player

654
00:32:50,045 --> 00:32:54,888
brain-o-vision we can often catch it earlier. Another

655
00:32:54,928 --> 00:32:58,729
attribute I like to consider is priority. Meaning when seeing

656
00:32:58,769 --> 00:33:01,631
lots of enemies on screen, which order to defeat them in.

657
00:33:02,381 --> 00:33:05,402
How urgently do I need to defeat this enemy relative to others?

658
00:33:06,302 --> 00:33:08,843
An example of a high priority enemy is the generator from

659
00:33:08,883 --> 00:33:12,044
gauntlet. It doesn't matter how many ghosts you kill, if you

660
00:33:12,064 --> 00:33:14,384
don't kill the bone piles first, they'll keep spawning more

661
00:33:14,404 --> 00:33:18,225
ghosts. The UFO from space invaders is an interesting case.

662
00:33:18,545 --> 00:33:21,626
You prioritize it not because it's threatening, but because

663
00:33:21,666 --> 00:33:23,947
it's worth a bunch of points and only on screen for a limited

664
00:33:23,987 --> 00:33:29,008
time. Let's think about priority some more. Suppose we have a

665
00:33:29,048 --> 00:33:30,108
group of basic grunts.

666
00:33:31,504 --> 00:33:32,745
Now let's add a healer to the group.

667
00:33:33,085 --> 00:33:34,365
If we try killing the grunts first,

668
00:33:34,785 --> 00:33:35,546
it'll take a long time,

669
00:33:35,586 --> 00:33:36,786
because the healer will keep them healed.

670
00:33:38,607 --> 00:33:41,448
So the correct play is to focus on killing the healer first,

671
00:33:41,888 --> 00:33:42,788
then take care of the grunts

672
00:33:42,848 --> 00:33:43,869
after the healer's been dealt with.

673
00:33:44,769 --> 00:33:45,389
But what about this?

674
00:33:46,530 --> 00:33:49,871
Let's instead add a high damage dealing archer to the group.

675
00:33:51,032 --> 00:33:53,232
In this case, the archer becomes our number one priority,

676
00:33:53,252 --> 00:33:54,793
because it's the more threatening unit.

677
00:33:54,913 --> 00:33:57,174
Again, it makes sense to prioritize

678
00:33:57,234 --> 00:33:58,514
killing the archer over the grunts.

679
00:33:59,452 --> 00:34:02,776
Now, as long as in this weird hypothetical game we're only

680
00:34:02,816 --> 00:34:05,899
presented with units in these two formations of healers and

681
00:34:05,919 --> 00:34:09,744
grunts and archers and grunts, the healer and the archer would

682
00:34:09,764 --> 00:34:14,228
seem as the exact same unit in terms of priority. Even though

683
00:34:14,248 --> 00:34:17,252
they perform vastly different roles. Just something to keep in

684
00:34:17,292 --> 00:34:17,412
mind.

685
00:34:18,464 --> 00:34:21,165
Fact is a lot of enemies we design tend to fall into this

686
00:34:21,265 --> 00:34:24,726
high priority deal with me first category. That's why it's good

687
00:34:24,746 --> 00:34:27,466
to explore the other end of the spectrum and design enemies

688
00:34:27,486 --> 00:34:30,667
that are best dealt with last. Both these guys get mad and

689
00:34:30,687 --> 00:34:32,907
become more deadly after you damage them. So it's best to

690
00:34:32,967 --> 00:34:35,688
ignore them as long as you have other enemies to deal with.

691
00:34:36,788 --> 00:34:40,449
Enemies that have lots of HP and do low amounts of damage also

692
00:34:40,489 --> 00:34:42,090
fit into this deal with me last category.

693
00:34:43,636 --> 00:34:46,218
Another attribute we can consider is timing. It often

694
00:34:46,238 --> 00:34:48,580
involves having an enemy that's more dangerous during certain

695
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:51,702
times or likewise more vulnerable during certain times.

696
00:34:52,163 --> 00:34:54,925
A prime example of this is the piranha plant from Super Mario.

697
00:34:55,665 --> 00:34:58,147
It's safe to pass while it's retracted into the pipe but

698
00:34:58,187 --> 00:35:01,850
dangerous otherwise. The lava bubble is another bad guy from

699
00:35:01,890 --> 00:35:05,012
Super Mario that hops in and out of the lava and requires timing

700
00:35:05,052 --> 00:35:05,433
to avoid.

701
00:35:07,095 --> 00:35:09,577
If we're observant and we use player brain vision, we might

702
00:35:09,717 --> 00:35:12,320
discover some similarities between these two units. I

703
00:35:12,380 --> 00:35:15,262
initially didn't think of these as being very similar, but in

704
00:35:15,282 --> 00:35:17,705
researching this talk, I realized they're both timing

705
00:35:17,725 --> 00:35:21,168
based enemies with up and down movement. The only differences

706
00:35:21,288 --> 00:35:24,651
are the lava bubble is immune to Mario's fireball and only found

707
00:35:24,691 --> 00:35:28,275
in lava. Now this is our own game. It would then be up to us

708
00:35:28,295 --> 00:35:30,817
to decide if these small differences were enough.

709
00:35:31,996 --> 00:35:34,797
All right. On to the next attribute. When most games in

710
00:35:34,817 --> 00:35:39,500
your game do close range attacks, you should shake things

711
00:35:39,580 --> 00:35:42,422
up by offering some enemies that are long ranged. The catapult

712
00:35:42,442 --> 00:35:45,283
zombie and hammer brothers are examples of long range enemies

713
00:35:45,343 --> 00:35:48,945
in games where most enemies are close ranged. Likewise, if most

714
00:35:48,965 --> 00:35:51,607
of the enemies in your game are long range, consider throwing in

715
00:35:51,647 --> 00:35:55,529
a close range enemy to liven things up. A lot of these

716
00:35:55,629 --> 00:35:58,911
attributes come down to being observant of what happens often

717
00:35:58,931 --> 00:36:01,252
in your game and designing things to disrupt that.

718
00:36:02,067 --> 00:36:03,476
Which brings us to our next attribute.

719
00:36:04,577 --> 00:36:07,260
A good way of coming up with new enemies is to think about what

720
00:36:07,440 --> 00:36:09,862
actions the player does most often in your game, then come

721
00:36:09,902 --> 00:36:12,144
up with an enemy that counters that action to shake things up.

722
00:36:12,945 --> 00:36:15,987
In Super Mario, the most common action to defeat enemies is to

723
00:36:16,007 --> 00:36:18,610
stomp on them. So halfway through the game, the spiny

724
00:36:18,630 --> 00:36:22,013
enemy is introduced, which you obviously can't stomp on. Along

725
00:36:22,033 --> 00:36:24,555
the same lines, the buzzy beetle is immune to fireballs, another

726
00:36:24,595 --> 00:36:28,118
common action of Mario's. Both enemies do their job of keeping

727
