965
00:48:14,886 --> 00:48:17,207
So we got this awesome visual design document.

966
00:48:17,527 --> 00:48:18,968
And everyone kind of understood, oh, so this

967
00:48:19,008 --> 00:48:20,249
is the direction traversal is going.

968
00:48:21,370 --> 00:48:22,030
And that was great.

969
00:48:22,090 --> 00:48:23,071
So they started implementing it.

970
00:48:23,291 --> 00:48:25,532
And then a few months later, it's like, OK,

971
00:48:25,552 --> 00:48:26,573
so what's going on with traversal?

972
00:48:26,953 --> 00:48:29,975
Well, go play the game.

973
00:48:30,475 --> 00:48:32,637
Because at that point, the game was the best documentation

974
00:48:32,677 --> 00:48:33,857
you could have for this system.

975
00:48:33,957 --> 00:48:35,638
And when it changed, there was no reason

976
00:48:35,678 --> 00:48:37,660
to change documentation and inform the whole team.

977
00:48:37,980 --> 00:48:39,041
You just go and you play the game.

978
00:48:39,901 --> 00:48:43,963
some other considerations to deal with. Write docs when

979
00:48:44,003 --> 00:48:48,325
needed, not before. Don't write for an audience that doesn't

980
00:48:48,365 --> 00:48:51,086
exist yet. So some people might not like this one. What it

981
00:48:51,146 --> 00:48:54,447
means is let's say you're designing a boss and you have

982
00:48:54,728 --> 00:48:57,429
your high level approval. Well, you can go in and you can write

983
00:48:57,529 --> 00:48:59,810
all the details for it, but it might not get implemented for

984
00:48:59,850 --> 00:49:02,811
six months. And everyone knows that in those six months, a ton

985
00:49:02,831 --> 00:49:06,633
of things are going to change. So I would argue that you wait

986
00:49:06,713 --> 00:49:09,334
until the last possible practical.

987
00:49:09,854 --> 00:49:12,575
minute before you write that documentation. So you know who

988
00:49:12,595 --> 00:49:14,836
is actually implementing it so you can write for that person.

989
00:49:16,577 --> 00:49:18,818
Obviously the flip side of this is that suddenly you get

990
00:49:18,858 --> 00:49:22,359
documentation. And that means you have to have a really fast

991
00:49:22,399 --> 00:49:24,900
turnaround and be able to do documentation and be really

992
00:49:24,941 --> 00:49:29,242
flexible with it. So that's one of the downsides. And this also

993
00:49:29,302 --> 00:49:32,744
runs counter to a plan it out first mentality or it appears to

994
00:49:32,804 --> 00:49:36,445
on the surface at least. Because there's the idea that we want to

995
00:49:36,505 --> 00:49:37,406
plan everything and then.

996
00:49:37,426 --> 00:49:39,287
We're working on this stuff through the software team.

997
00:49:39,950 --> 00:49:42,512
Plan it out first as much as possible before you start

998
00:49:42,832 --> 00:49:44,053
investing the money to implement it.

999
00:49:44,373 --> 00:49:48,657
But I would argue that you are your own reader, so you should

1000
00:49:48,697 --> 00:49:52,960
be able to and you can write documentation as yourself as the

1001
00:49:53,021 --> 00:49:55,763
reader and the purpose is to plan, right?

1002
00:49:55,863 --> 00:49:59,766
So it doesn't entirely strip out the idea of plan it out first.

1003
00:50:01,267 --> 00:50:04,991
So it's not an excuse to avoid documentation.

1004
00:50:05,951 --> 00:50:09,735
Even if you're waiting up to the last practical minute, you're still writing more documents,

1005
00:50:09,795 --> 00:50:10,395
not fewer.

1006
00:50:11,456 --> 00:50:13,498
It doesn't replace every document that you make.

1007
00:50:14,279 --> 00:50:16,501
There's still going to be times where you need to make that, you know.

1008
00:50:17,441 --> 00:50:23,366
20 page document that some people may or may not read. And it's sad when they don't read it. But I

1009
00:50:23,406 --> 00:50:29,851
would argue that we should try and make it as actionable as possible. So this is an example of a

1010
00:50:29,931 --> 00:50:36,677
document for scribble knots that I made. And I had to be 25 pages. So I just said, okay, every page

1011
00:50:36,737 --> 00:50:40,500
needs to have sort of an actionable thing that you can do with it. And split it up.

1012
00:50:41,180 --> 00:50:45,801
And then just to wrap up, I just want to acknowledge that this talk may not work so well if you're

1013
00:50:45,821 --> 00:50:51,042
an indie or you work alone, because you are making all the documentation for yourself

1014
00:50:51,122 --> 00:50:51,943
and not a big team.

1015
00:50:52,903 --> 00:50:57,744
And then the last thing is that sometimes it's difficult to onboard new people if you

1016
00:50:57,884 --> 00:51:01,865
don't have any documentation for features that exist, but we already have the problem

1017
00:51:01,925 --> 00:51:05,986
where our documentation that exists is either out of date or it doesn't exist.

1018
00:51:06,026 --> 00:51:10,367
So it's sort of like which is your least worst case scenario.

1019
00:51:10,627 --> 00:51:13,793
So that's it. That's my argument for make actionable

1020
00:51:13,813 --> 00:51:15,255
documentation. Thank you.

1021
00:51:20,505 --> 00:51:21,447
It's all good.

1022
00:51:23,458 --> 00:51:24,258
So thank you, Liz.

1023
00:51:24,298 --> 00:51:25,919
We are running a little low on time.

1024
00:51:25,939 --> 00:51:28,239
So I'm going to move right along here to our final speaker,

1025
00:51:28,840 --> 00:51:31,401
is Michael DePlatter, talking about a subject dear to my

1026
00:51:31,441 --> 00:51:31,601
heart.

1027
00:51:31,641 --> 00:51:33,801
Often we think about game systems as intuitive or sticky

1028
00:51:33,821 --> 00:51:36,002
or challenging or good for flow.

1029
00:51:36,102 --> 00:51:38,583
But what if they are good for producing humanity?

1030
00:51:38,663 --> 00:51:41,064
Michael has been working in games for some time, worked on

1031
00:51:41,084 --> 00:51:44,085
everything from sports games to Total War franchise to

1032
00:51:44,145 --> 00:51:46,106
2014's Game of the Year, Shadow of Mordor.

1033
00:51:46,226 --> 00:51:46,806
Michael DePlatter.

1034
00:51:51,120 --> 00:51:52,421
Hello, is that coming through?

1035
00:51:52,441 --> 00:51:55,844
Yeah, I just love GDC so much.

1036
00:51:55,904 --> 00:51:57,726
All these talks are so inspiring,

1037
00:51:57,746 --> 00:51:59,948
and I guess really that's probably the number one

1038
00:52:00,148 --> 00:52:03,512
takeaway from this talk is how much

1039
00:52:04,352 --> 00:52:06,715
other games and multiple genres can inform

1040
00:52:07,556 --> 00:52:08,598
every game you're working on.

1041
00:52:08,638 --> 00:52:11,601
So this is really, as Richard was saying before,

1042
00:52:12,102 --> 00:52:16,027
a personal story in the sense of a specific case study

1043
00:52:16,307 --> 00:52:18,330
of how did sports games and war games

1044
00:52:18,410 --> 00:52:21,033
and real world references inform the Nemesis system.

1045
00:52:24,490 --> 00:52:26,351
And it's sort of a two-way street.

1046
00:52:26,411 --> 00:52:29,592
So the Nemesis system was something where we wanted players,

1047
00:52:29,952 --> 00:52:33,413
sorry, I should just explain, it was the key feature

1048
00:52:33,453 --> 00:52:35,974
of Shadow of Mordor, the open world action adventure game

1049
00:52:36,014 --> 00:52:38,715
we did last year where players have their own

1050
00:52:39,496 --> 00:52:40,696
unique and personal enemies.

1051
00:52:40,736 --> 00:52:43,077
We wanted to make it a villain simulator

1052
00:52:43,197 --> 00:52:44,917
and we wanted to make these really diverse

1053
00:52:44,957 --> 00:52:45,758
and meaningful enemies.

1054
00:52:47,694 --> 00:52:51,535
And what we wanted to do was to make them operate

1055
00:52:51,575 --> 00:52:54,777
according to the most real world intuitive rule set

1056
00:52:54,817 --> 00:52:58,919
that we could, so to find out about how do these

1057
00:52:58,979 --> 00:53:01,040
kind of stories get created in the real world

1058
00:53:01,080 --> 00:53:02,521
and how could we actually apply that

1059
00:53:02,581 --> 00:53:04,102
to the creation of our game.

1060
00:53:05,623 --> 00:53:08,444
And as we're looking at that, we really went back

1061
00:53:08,804 --> 00:53:12,186
and looked not just at action adventure games,

1062
00:53:12,226 --> 00:53:14,147
not just at games within our genres,

1063
00:53:14,167 --> 00:53:16,088
but also sports games, war games,

1064
00:53:16,228 --> 00:53:17,168
all sorts of different things.

1065
00:53:21,606 --> 00:53:24,708
And in particular, what we sort of looked at

1066
00:53:24,748 --> 00:53:29,111
was the way that sports is a real world system

1067
00:53:29,131 --> 00:53:30,492
that is actively designed.

1068
00:53:30,512 --> 00:53:34,334
You know, game designers work in sports.

1069
00:53:34,414 --> 00:53:37,576
You know, they design seasons, they design formats,

1070
00:53:37,616 --> 00:53:38,597
they design rules.

1071
00:53:39,357 --> 00:53:41,779
And the things that those seasons and rules do

1072
00:53:42,379 --> 00:53:44,380
is they generate stories.

1073
00:53:47,112 --> 00:53:48,852
The ways in which they generate stories

1074
00:53:49,132 --> 00:53:50,953
are through a lot of the same mechanics

1075
00:53:50,993 --> 00:53:53,614
that we see in books and movies and other media.

1076
00:53:54,134 --> 00:53:56,774
So they create and set up conflicts.

1077
00:53:58,015 --> 00:53:59,775
One of the things that was very important for us

1078
00:54:00,095 --> 00:54:04,037
is you don't have save game mechanics in sports.

1079
00:54:04,717 --> 00:54:07,658
The failure and the way in which time moves forward

1080
00:54:08,318 --> 00:54:11,519
is actually a key component of creating the drama

1081
00:54:11,599 --> 00:54:13,179
and creating the story.

1082
00:54:13,259 --> 00:54:15,880
So for example, if you lose the third match of the season,

1083
00:54:16,821 --> 00:54:18,442
you don't roll it back and play it again,

1084
00:54:18,462 --> 00:54:20,164
you have to overcome that loss.

1085
00:54:20,564 --> 00:54:25,028
And those sort of real world passage of time

1086
00:54:25,148 --> 00:54:27,350
is great for drama, it creates rivalries,

1087
00:54:27,490 --> 00:54:29,992
it creates comebacks, it creates underdogs,

1088
00:54:30,112 --> 00:54:32,074
it creates all of these.

1089
00:54:33,075 --> 00:54:34,996
personal dramas for players to overcome.

1090
00:54:35,777 --> 00:54:37,759
And that was something that we focused on a lot

1091
00:54:37,939 --> 00:54:41,782
with our system as well, and finding ways to

1092
00:54:42,503 --> 00:54:44,805
make that treatment of time tie together

1093
00:54:45,525 --> 00:54:48,808
with our fiction, which in this case was Lord of the Rings,

1094
00:54:49,709 --> 00:54:52,031
and a system of death and resurrection.

1095
00:54:52,071 --> 00:54:54,673
So time would move forward, and we would be creating

1096
00:54:54,713 --> 00:54:56,094
these personal stories with enemies.

1097
00:54:57,075 --> 00:54:59,117
And another thing, oh, excuse me, sorry,

1098
00:54:59,357 --> 00:55:01,999
end of the week, I'm finally hitting puberty.

1099
00:55:03,212 --> 00:55:07,315
And another thing that's very common

1100
00:55:07,516 --> 00:55:11,038
and we can see in sports, but also very much in drama,

1101
00:55:11,118 --> 00:55:14,401
whether it's Jane Austen or whether it's Patton

1102
00:55:14,521 --> 00:55:17,443
or whether it's Star Wars, is social structures

1103
00:55:17,483 --> 00:55:21,026
and social hierarchies underlie a lot of the most

1104
00:55:21,526 --> 00:55:22,887
emotionally affecting stories.

1105
00:55:22,927 --> 00:55:25,109
People that start on top and they have a fall

1106
00:55:25,149 --> 00:55:26,450
and move down in society.

1107
00:55:26,510 --> 00:55:29,432
People start at the bottom as a poor, innocent farm boy

1108
00:55:29,492 --> 00:55:30,413
and make their way up.

1109
00:55:31,233 --> 00:55:33,416
And so that was again something that was really interesting

1110
00:55:33,456 --> 00:55:35,478
for us to be able to simulate.

1111
00:55:35,518 --> 00:55:37,600
And by simulating these social structures,

1112
00:55:37,680 --> 00:55:40,323
time, these relationships, conflict,

1113
00:55:40,743 --> 00:55:43,806
to try and make something that's not a structured narrative

1114
00:55:43,866 --> 00:55:45,808
but creates the same sort of emotion

1115
00:55:45,848 --> 00:55:46,850
and the same connection.

1116
00:55:51,993 --> 00:55:56,276
And then as a specific example, going back to sports,

1117
00:55:56,776 --> 00:56:00,299
sports seasons are basically a three-act narrative structure.

1118
00:56:01,239 --> 00:56:03,861
You have Act One, where we see who the various teams are,

1119
00:56:03,901 --> 00:56:05,262
who are the favorites, what's going on,

1120
00:56:05,602 --> 00:56:07,003
and we have Act Two with this.

1121
00:56:07,643 --> 00:56:10,284
the sort of constant buildup of the action,

1122
00:56:10,324 --> 00:56:12,845
the highs and lows, and then act three,

1123
00:56:12,925 --> 00:56:15,506
they generally have a structure of the finals

1124
00:56:15,566 --> 00:56:17,406
and the final climax and the grand final.

1125
00:56:17,446 --> 00:56:21,027
So even though the plot is basically the same every year,

1126
00:56:21,487 --> 00:56:24,168
the stories and the dramas of it are incredibly dynamic.

1127
00:56:24,548 --> 00:56:26,729
And that was a model which we wanted to take

1128
00:56:26,769 --> 00:56:30,350
and apply into our genre, which was action adventure.

1129
00:56:30,430 --> 00:56:31,010
And the other one.

1130
00:56:32,371 --> 00:56:33,573
which was very important for us

1131
00:56:33,653 --> 00:56:35,436
and often isn't the case in games.

1132
00:56:35,736 --> 00:56:38,580
In games, there's the tendency when you fail

1133
00:56:38,621 --> 00:56:40,143
to say, okay, go back and do that again.

1134
00:56:40,183 --> 00:56:42,066
We're going to wave our hands and say it didn't happen.

1135
00:56:42,546 --> 00:56:45,410
But, as I say, in sports, whether it's an injury or a loss,

1136
00:56:46,812 --> 00:56:48,853
that failure is actually embraced and used

1137
00:56:48,873 --> 00:56:52,435
to create more drama, and that was absolutely core to us.

1138
00:56:52,475 --> 00:56:54,976
We wanted, when you died, not to say,

1139
00:56:55,136 --> 00:56:56,717
okay, that's a failure, you should go back

1140
00:56:56,777 --> 00:56:59,699
and do that again, but you've actually created the seed

1141
00:56:59,739 --> 00:57:02,400
of an exciting and personal story and this vendetta

1142
00:57:02,440 --> 00:57:04,481
and this personal relationship against the guy

1143
00:57:04,521 --> 00:57:05,201
that defeated you.

1144
00:57:05,842 --> 00:57:08,363
And of course, the other place that that happens constantly

1145
00:57:08,843 --> 00:57:11,564
and time moves forward, we create these personal rivalries

1146
00:57:11,644 --> 00:57:14,166
is multiplayer games, so, you know, Call of Duty.

1147
00:57:15,567 --> 00:57:18,210
and so on, which was another, we were sort of trying

1148
00:57:18,250 --> 00:57:21,213
to create the types of relatedness and grudges

1149
00:57:21,233 --> 00:57:24,697
you get against other human beings onto our NPCs.

1150
00:57:24,717 --> 00:57:26,499
We wanted to make them as human as possible

1151
00:57:26,539 --> 00:57:29,462
with the goal of maximizing players' emotion.

1152
00:57:30,403 --> 00:57:33,706
And all of these sort of systems for creating stories

1153
00:57:33,766 --> 00:57:36,669
and drama aren't within the framework of

1154
00:57:38,410 --> 00:57:40,934
Even non-linear narratives or branching narratives

1155
00:57:40,974 --> 00:57:43,237
are the sorts of things that we can see in RPGs.

1156
00:57:43,297 --> 00:57:46,321
It's generally trying to actually make a system

1157
00:57:46,361 --> 00:57:48,424
that generates drama and relationships.

1158
00:57:50,650 --> 00:57:53,393
And something else we looked at from sports and took is

1159
00:57:54,254 --> 00:57:57,317
that it does, it creates stories at two scales.

1160
00:57:57,357 --> 00:58:00,760
You have this overarching narrative of the conflict

1161
00:58:00,800 --> 00:58:03,163
between the teams, who's going to win, who's going to lose.

1162
00:58:03,723 --> 00:58:05,905
But then within that, you also have the creation

1163
00:58:05,945 --> 00:58:07,167
of very personal narratives.

1164
00:58:07,207 --> 00:58:09,148
So you have heroes and villains emerging,

1165
00:58:09,168 --> 00:58:11,070
you have revenge stories emerging,

1166
00:58:11,351 --> 00:58:12,652
you have underdogs that come up.

1167
00:58:13,112 --> 00:58:15,993
You have grudges, but all of these individual

1168
00:58:16,053 --> 00:58:19,015
personal stories are taking place within this framework

1169
00:58:19,235 --> 00:58:20,815
of a larger conflict.

1170
00:58:21,716 --> 00:58:24,117
And again, although we see it in the real world,

1171
00:58:24,237 --> 00:58:26,858
in sports, it's something that mapped very nicely

1172
00:58:26,898 --> 00:58:28,739
to Mordor and Orc society for us.

1173
00:58:31,880 --> 00:58:32,120
And then.

1174
00:58:33,773 --> 00:58:35,494
Another thing that's really interesting is there's whole

1175
00:58:35,694 --> 00:58:39,575
sections of journalism basically that are dedicated

1176
00:58:40,035 --> 00:58:43,716
to creating and narrativizing and weaving written stories

1177
00:58:43,956 --> 00:58:46,456
out of what is basically statistical analysis.

1178
00:58:47,016 --> 00:58:50,077
People take stats of the results of different players,

1179
00:58:50,137 --> 00:58:52,197
different teams, and they'll turn those

1180
00:58:52,257 --> 00:58:53,778
into written narratives that people find

1181
00:58:53,798 --> 00:58:55,958
really emotionally engaging and will follow.

1182
00:58:57,339 --> 00:58:59,240
Everything that we did, even though the underlying

1183
00:58:59,320 --> 00:59:02,402
complexity of the whole system and the Nemesis system

1184
00:59:03,363 --> 00:59:05,624
under the hood is obviously enormously complex,

1185
00:59:05,724 --> 00:59:08,386
the way we always wanted to surface that to people

1186
00:59:08,446 --> 00:59:10,868
is in a naturalistic story.

1187
00:59:11,428 --> 00:59:13,590
One of the ways we sort of test that ourselves is,

1188
00:59:14,430 --> 00:59:16,011
and we did this on Total War as well,

1189
00:59:16,051 --> 00:59:17,892
and you also see this on sports games,

1190
00:59:18,133 --> 00:59:21,074
is if people are writing stories about our game,

1191
00:59:21,255 --> 00:59:23,836
is the language they're using to express their story

1192
00:59:23,956 --> 00:59:24,897
sound like they're really...

1193
00:59:25,437 --> 00:59:26,998
invested in that world.

1194
00:59:31,040 --> 00:59:32,861
And then, we have to speed up a bit,

1195
00:59:32,921 --> 00:59:36,183
but war shares a lot of the same structures,

1196
00:59:36,323 --> 00:59:40,385
and again, war, like sports, not only creates these stories,

1197
00:59:40,445 --> 00:59:44,087
but is very often a reference point for

1198
00:59:44,547 --> 00:59:46,729
for entire genres of fiction.

1199
00:59:46,789 --> 00:59:49,790
So we have entire genres of movies around sports,

1200
00:59:49,830 --> 00:59:51,111
we obviously have a lot of genres,

1201
00:59:52,112 --> 00:59:53,413
and a lot of films around war,

1202
00:59:53,453 --> 00:59:56,314
because they share those dramatic traits of conflict,

1203
00:59:56,354 --> 01:00:00,877
of escalation towards a epic finale, a personal story.

1204
01:00:00,957 --> 01:00:02,638
So, you know, Band of Brothers,

1205
01:00:03,659 --> 01:00:07,181
Platoon, within the context of this larger epic conflict.

1206
01:00:07,701 --> 01:00:10,082
So games like Civilization are obviously very good

1207
01:00:10,102 --> 01:00:11,984
at simulating these large-scale conflicts,

1208
01:00:12,004 --> 01:00:12,664
but we wanted to see,

1209
01:00:12,684 --> 01:00:13,324
where else can we put...

1210
01:00:14,045 --> 01:00:16,025
personal stories and nest them within that,

1211
01:00:16,705 --> 01:00:21,087
and an emphasis on human hierarchies and social structures,

1212
01:00:21,147 --> 01:00:22,627
whether that's generals and troops

1213
01:00:22,687 --> 01:00:25,008
in the military hierarchies or sports teams.

1214
01:00:27,288 --> 01:00:30,489
And then just quickly, a couple of specific examples

1215
01:00:30,649 --> 01:00:34,910
of how we use real world references to create stories,

1216
01:00:34,990 --> 01:00:36,651
even going back to Total War,

1217
01:00:36,771 --> 01:00:39,811
which was where I was working before Shadow of Mordor.

1218
01:00:41,491 --> 01:00:45,574
People are also very, very keen to project agency

1219
01:00:45,614 --> 01:00:49,376
and project character onto NPCs.

1220
01:00:49,436 --> 01:00:53,479
So by applying traits, personality traits,

1221
01:00:53,539 --> 01:00:54,940
onto our generals and our characters,

1222
01:00:55,100 --> 01:00:57,622
it just changed them from being collections of stats.

1223
01:00:58,222 --> 01:01:00,223
into being characters people could relate to.

1224
01:01:00,343 --> 01:01:02,323
And Darkest Dungeons, obviously another game

1225
01:01:02,363 --> 01:01:03,604
that does that extremely well.

1226
01:01:04,384 --> 01:01:05,704
And we tried to do that with our Orcs,

1227
01:01:05,744 --> 01:01:07,365
in particular their hates and fears,

1228
01:01:07,925 --> 01:01:09,665
which was simultaneously trying to make them

1229
01:01:09,865 --> 01:01:11,466
do something that George spoke to before

1230
01:01:11,486 --> 01:01:13,026
of differentiating them as enemies

1231
01:01:13,086 --> 01:01:16,047
by making them block your different abilities.

1232
01:01:16,327 --> 01:01:18,547
Our equivalent, we had players spreading fires everywhere,

1233
01:01:18,607 --> 01:01:20,108
so we gave guys that hated fire,

1234
01:01:20,188 --> 01:01:23,289
so now they could block and come back at you as a result

1235
01:01:23,349 --> 01:01:24,349
and punish you for doing that.

1236
01:01:25,949 --> 01:01:30,412
Another example we had of using sort of a drama mechanic

1237
01:01:31,073 --> 01:01:35,296
in concert with the balancing mechanics was in Rome,

1238
01:01:35,336 --> 01:01:37,778
very often the Roman Empire from the start of the game

1239
01:01:37,818 --> 01:01:40,320
would cross the world, start dominating the world,

1240
01:01:40,360 --> 01:01:41,882
and then you'd get to this point in the game,

1241
01:01:41,922 --> 01:01:44,844
we found, where the final stages of a strategy game

1242
01:01:44,884 --> 01:01:46,866
could be relatively boring, mopping up.

1243
01:01:46,966 --> 01:01:49,648
So we injected this drama of the civil war.

1244
01:01:49,688 --> 01:01:52,190
At that point, Rome would turn on itself, it would split,

1245
01:01:52,210 --> 01:01:54,672
you'd have all these family dramas and rivalries.

1246
01:01:56,450 --> 01:01:59,091
Of course, the big difference with Shadow of Mordor

1247
01:01:59,111 --> 01:02:00,691
from big strategy games like Rome

1248
01:02:00,711 --> 01:02:03,132
is that we wanted to make it personal.

1249
01:02:03,152 --> 01:02:06,073
And as I say, we built it around those principles

1250
01:02:06,113 --> 01:02:09,834
that we see in these real world story creating systems

1251
01:02:10,034 --> 01:02:13,355
of sports and warfare, which is basing it around conflict,

1252
01:02:13,815 --> 01:02:15,776
making the time always move forward

1253
01:02:15,796 --> 01:02:17,656
so we can build these personal relationships,

1254
01:02:18,216 --> 01:02:21,697
embracing failure as a chance to create stories.

1255
01:02:23,438 --> 01:02:28,203
and also focusing on social structures and human hierarchies.

1256
01:02:28,343 --> 01:02:33,809
And again, we can see that in Jane Austen, we can see it in Mexican prisons, we can see it in sports teams.

1257
01:02:36,484 --> 01:02:39,146
But then the other thing we had to do is figure

1258
01:02:39,507 --> 01:02:41,209
how do we surface that to the player?

1259
01:02:41,249 --> 01:02:43,051
How do we narrativize that in a way

1260
01:02:43,111 --> 01:02:45,193
that feels really powerfully like a story?

1261
01:02:47,255 --> 01:02:49,878
And that was where we put an enormous amount of emphasis

1262
01:02:50,218 --> 01:02:54,703
in basically the clashes and the showdowns

1263
01:02:54,783 --> 01:02:56,746
and having these guys actually remember you.

1264
01:02:58,427 --> 01:03:00,571
Players are always creating stories in their own heads

1265
01:03:00,611 --> 01:03:03,175
and are really willing to have you reinforce

1266
01:03:03,215 --> 01:03:05,118
the meaning of those stories by speaking to them.

1267
01:03:05,158 --> 01:03:06,641
If you say, you did this to me,

1268
01:03:06,701 --> 01:03:08,483
players are absolutely like, oh my god, I did.

1269
01:03:08,684 --> 01:03:09,846
I am the center of the universe.

1270
01:03:09,886 --> 01:03:12,911
Human beings are amazingly egocentric and it's great.

1271
01:03:15,407 --> 01:03:17,568
And so, then this was just other examples.

1272
01:03:17,588 --> 01:03:19,688
You know, we were obviously focused on a single player

1273
01:03:19,748 --> 01:03:24,069
action adventure game, but there's so many other games now

1274
01:03:24,109 --> 01:03:26,770
where you see this possibility of people creating narratives

1275
01:03:26,810 --> 01:03:28,470
about what they've done within these worlds.

1276
01:03:28,850 --> 01:03:30,811
And what's exciting about something like DayZ

1277
01:03:30,891 --> 01:03:32,251
is when people write their narratives

1278
01:03:32,291 --> 01:03:34,712
of their game experience, it reads exactly like

1279
01:03:35,452 --> 01:03:38,073
a post-apocalyptic zombie horror.

1280
01:03:38,093 --> 01:03:40,173
So the same psychological forces,

1281
01:03:40,233 --> 01:03:43,594
the same stories are getting triggered by the same events.

1282
01:03:43,674 --> 01:03:43,974
And that's...

1283
01:03:45,175 --> 01:03:47,838
That takes me to the last slide, which is that Monolith,

1284
01:03:48,238 --> 01:03:50,100
the way we work and our framework,

1285
01:03:50,941 --> 01:03:53,144
is very much represented, you can, in this book,

1286
01:03:53,164 --> 01:03:55,406
glue to games, but there's a theory,

1287
01:03:55,466 --> 01:03:57,528
player engagement through need satisfaction,

1288
01:03:57,568 --> 01:04:00,031
which is a theory of player engagement

1289
01:04:00,071 --> 01:04:02,894
based on the psychological self-determination theory.

1290
01:04:03,415 --> 01:04:05,017
And basically what it boils down to,

1291
01:04:05,897 --> 01:04:07,858
is that the things that motivate people

1292
01:04:07,898 --> 01:04:09,759
to keep playing your game are the same things

1293
01:04:09,799 --> 01:04:12,520
that motivate people to do things in the rest of their life,

1294
01:04:12,540 --> 01:04:15,401
which is autonomy, people want their decisions

1295
01:04:15,541 --> 01:04:18,683
to have the ability to make meaningful decisions,

1296
01:04:19,163 --> 01:04:21,704
competence, people want to learn

1297
01:04:21,904 --> 01:04:23,685
and sometimes they want to feel like they're kicking ass,

1298
01:04:24,405 --> 01:04:27,206
and relatedness, people want to connect

1299
01:04:27,326 --> 01:04:28,487
with other living things.

1300
01:04:29,247 --> 01:04:31,809
that emotion actually doesn't really differentiate

1301
01:04:31,829 --> 01:04:33,891
very much whether it's an NPC or a human.

1302
01:04:33,911 --> 01:04:36,774
You're actually filling the same psychological needs.

1303
01:04:36,854 --> 01:04:39,876
So what we were really doing is looking at the real world

1304
01:04:39,956 --> 01:04:41,938
to inform what we did in the game.

1305
01:04:41,998 --> 01:04:44,460
So strongly recommend glued to games.

1306
01:04:46,121 --> 01:04:49,824
And then see how you can use real world systems like that

1307
01:04:49,864 --> 01:04:52,907
to maybe inform getting players to get invested

1308
01:04:52,947 --> 01:04:54,168
in the stories within your game.

